## Description {#details}

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymreader">GsymReader</a> is used to read GSYM data from a file or buffer.

This class is optimized for very quick lookups when the endianness matches the host system. The <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header">Header</a>, address table, address info offsets, and file table is designed to be mmap&#39;ed as read only into memory and used without any parsing needed. If the endianness doesn&#39;t match, we swap these objects and tables into GsymReader::SwappedData and then point our header and ArrayRefs to this swapped internal data.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymreader">GsymReader</a> objects must use one of the static functions to create an instance: GsymReader::openFile(...) and GsymReader::copyBuffer(...).

### getFunctionInfo() {#a891f5398a526e0de9d2b5006559ef594}

Get the full function info for an address.

This should be called when a client will store a copy of the complete <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> for a given address. For one off lookups, use the <a href="#ad5768ee08d5c7c9b431387ce9b03a6e9">lookup()</a> function below.

### lookup() {#ad5768ee08d5c7c9b431387ce9b03a6e9}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>llvm::Expected&lt; LookupResult &gt; GsymReader::lookup (uint64&#95;t Addr, std::optional&lt; <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> &gt; &#42; MergedFuncsData=nullptr) const</>}>
Lookup an address in the a GSYM.

Lookup just the information needed for a specific address <em>Addr</em>. This function is faster that calling <a href="#a891f5398a526e0de9d2b5006559ef594">getFunctionInfo()</a> as it will only return information that pertains to <em>Addr</em> and allows the parsing to skip any extra information encoded for other addresses. For example the line table parsing can stop when a matching <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/lineentry">LineEntry</a> has been fouhnd, and the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/inlineinfo">InlineInfo</a> can stop parsing early once a match has been found and also skip information that doesn&#39;t match. This avoids memory allocations and is much faster for lookups.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Addr">A virtual address from the orignal object file to lookup.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="MergedFuncsData">A pointer to an optional <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> that, if non-null, will be set to the raw data of the MergedFunctionInfo, if present.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
An expected <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/lookupresult">LookupResult</a> that contains only the information needed for the current address, or an error object that indicates reason for failing to lookup the address.
</SectionUser>

Declaration at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h/#l00139">139</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h">GsymReader.h</a>, definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-cpp/#l00338">338</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-cpp">GsymReader.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### addressForIndex() {#a938be134329f4243053d957980a79724}

<MemberDefinition
  template={<>template &lt;class T&gt;</>}
  prototype={<>std::optional&lt; uint64&#95;t &gt; llvm::gsym::GsymReader::addressForIndex (size&#95;t Index) const</>}
  labels = {["inline", "protected"]}>
Get an appropriate address from the address table.

The address table in the GSYM file is stored as array of 1, 2, 4 or 8 byte address offsets from the The <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#af3a0fa4fd0587b1bcb2e1979bbe3c747">gsym::Header::BaseAddress</a>. The table is stored internally as a array of bytes that are in the correct endianness. In order to extract an address from the address table we must access the address offset using the correct size and then add it to the BaseAddress in the header.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Index">An index into the AddrOffsets array.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
An virtual address that matches the original object file for the address as the specified index, or std::nullopt if Index is out of bounds.
</SectionUser>

  template={<>template &lt;class T&gt;</>}
  prototype={<>ArrayRef&lt; T &gt; llvm::gsym::GsymReader::getAddrOffsets () const</>}
  labels = {["inline", "protected"]}>
Get an appropriate address info offsets array.

The address table in the GSYM file is stored as array of 1, 2, 4 or 8 byte offsets from the The <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/header/#af3a0fa4fd0587b1bcb2e1979bbe3c747">gsym::Header::BaseAddress</a>. The table is stored internally as a array of bytes that are in the correct endianness. When we access this table we must get an array that matches those sizes. This templatized helper function is used when accessing address offsets in the AddrOffsets member variable.


<SectionUser title="Returns">
An <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/arrayref">ArrayRef</a> of an appropriate address offset size.
</SectionUser>

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h/#l00291">291</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h">GsymReader.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### getFunctionInfoDataForAddress() {#af15b2b0c7e2abba2d3e36989685d800f}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>llvm::Expected&lt; DataExtractor &gt; GsymReader::getFunctionInfoDataForAddress (uint64&#95;t Addr, uint64&#95;t &amp; FuncStartAddr) const</>}
  labels = {["protected"]}>
Given an address, find the correct function info data and function address.

Binary search the address table and find the matching address info and make sure that the function info contains the address. GSYM allows functions to overlap, and the most debug info is contained in the first entries due to the sorting when GSYM files are created. We can have multiple function info that start at the same address only if their address range doesn&#39;t match. So find the first entry that matches <em>Addr</em> and iterate forward until we find one that contains the address.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="[in] Addr">A virtual address that matches the original object file to lookup.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="[out] FuncStartAddr">A virtual address that is the base address of the function that is used for decoding the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
An valid data extractor on success, or an error if we fail to find the address in a function info or corrrectly decode the data
</SectionUser>

Declaration at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h/#l00408">408</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-h">GsymReader.h</a>, definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-cpp/#l00256">256</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/gsymreader-cpp">GsymReader.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

</SectionDefinition>
